There are few south Asian restaurants that I give a perfect rating too in the Bay Area. Little Nepal is definitely one of them. Our visit to them was perfect. We were a group of four that went to them after a go car trip in San Francisco. We reached there at 5 after 5 pm and were immediately seated. While we decided on our courses, we asked for chai and it was promptly delivered. The menus have good descriptions and we went for a meal for two (they were more than happy to accommodate vegetarian substitutions), a curry with goat and a curry with shrimp. Along with each of the entrees came some white rice and naan. The servings were perfect. I would also recommend the lentil soup (it goes great with the white rice) Overall my experience was great and my only wish was that I was hungrier. Will definitely go back there soon.

Terrific for take out... but dining in is a great experience too. Owner is lovely. Food is great.

My friend and I came here on a chilly Sunday evening around 8:30pm. One guest was just leaving, otherwise, it was just us and then another group that showed up around 9:30pm. The ambiance is warm and calming and staff is friendly. For appetizer, we ordered: Himalayan Momo (We ordered vegetable) Minced chicken, pork or vegetable wrapped in flour dough and steamed. Served with chutney sauce made of sesame, chili and tomato. $6.99 For main entrees we ordered: Alu Tama Bodi Potato, black-eyed beans, and bamboo shoot cooked with fresh tomatoes, garlic, ginger and spices. $11.99 (a la carte) Tofu Tarkari (We substituted paneer) Tofu and green beans cooked in light cream with fresh tomatoes, garlic, ginger and spices. $11.99 (a la carte) The momo's were nice. The momo sauce was good, could have had a little more pop and flavor to it though, maybe some salt. For the tarkari, we substituted paneer for the tofu. As a paneer tikka masala fan, this was tasty and quite filling because of the creaminess. The green beans were a nice touch. The bean dish was interesting and different with the bamboo shoots addition, but I'd say this dish was very light and delicious. Also, a more healthy pick. The naan and rice come with order of an entree and the naan and rice we're done right. I'd recommended trying out this restaurant. Excuse the messy food/table in the photos!

With tax and tip my beverage-less meal came to $30.

We are definitely regulars now and I highly recommend this place!!!!

About the Business

Business owner information

Nepal N.

Manager

Traditional Nepalese food using the finest locally-sourced ingredients from the Bay Area. This food is from Northern India and Tibet. The Nepalese cuisine tends to reflect the unique geographical position of Nepal, which is wedged between India to the south and Tibet to the north. Their contrasting influences create a complex nepali cultural synthesis, which manifests itself also in the lively interaction of the remarkably diverse nepali ethnic groups and religious traditions. Likewise its cuisine is influenced by both the dishes from the indian planes and the exotic specialties of the high Himalayas. But it reflects also the diversity and the spirit of Nepal in the variety and the balance of its gastronomical offerings (somewhat fiery at times, but with various degrees of milder components).…

    My friend and I came here on a chilly Sunday evening around 8:30pm. One guest was just leaving, otherwise, it was just us and then another group that showed up around 9:30pm. The ambiance is warm and calming and staff is friendly.

    For appetizer, we ordered:

    Himalayan Momo (We ordered vegetable)
    Minced chicken, pork or vegetable wrapped in flour dough and steamed. Served with chutney sauce made of sesame, chili and tomato.
    $6.99

    For main entrees we ordered:

    Alu Tama Bodi
    Potato, black-eyed beans, and bamboo shoot cooked with fresh tomatoes, garlic, ginger and spices.
    $11.99 (a la carte)

    Tofu Tarkari (We substituted paneer)
    Tofu and green beans cooked in light cream with fresh tomatoes, garlic, ginger and spices.
    $11.99 (a la carte)

    The momo's were nice. The momo sauce was good, could have had a little more pop and flavor to it though, maybe some salt.

    For the tarkari, we substituted paneer for the tofu. As a paneer tikka masala fan, this was tasty and quite filling because of the creaminess. The green beans were a nice touch.

    The bean dish was interesting and different with the bamboo shoots addition, but I'd say this dish was very light and delicious. Also, a more healthy pick.

    The naan and rice come with order of an entree and the naan and rice we're done right.

    I'd recommended trying out this restaurant.

    Excuse the messy food/table in the photos!
